INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('820', '0', '2012-08-18 21:02:47', '2012-08-18 19:02:47', 'DASHWOODSTOCK 2012\n\nCAROUSEL + TERMINAL GODS + SCARLET ECHO + THE BRASSIC + THE GAA GAA\'S + CERI JAMES + FIELD OF WOLVES + RICHIE PHILLIPS\n\nSaturday 8th September 2012 // 4pm - 11pm // FREE ENTRY\n\nDashwood Social Club, 2 Limestone Walk, Thamesmead DA18 4BW\n\n///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////\n\nCAROUSEL // www.facebook.com/CarouselUkMusic\n\nCarousel are a three-piece acoustic band from Mottingham, South-East London. The band were formed in 2008 and have perfected their craft writing and performing at several venues in London and throughout 15 cities in the UK. The band shares a common passion for melancholic and powerful folk-pop that is reminiscent of Mumford &amp; Sons and Fleet Foxes.\n\nCarousel performed their first single ‘Writers Block’ in front of stunned audiences including; The Daily Mirror, Mail on Sunday, and celebrities at the National Luxury &amp; Lifestyle Awards 2012\n\nDebut single ‘Writers Block’ (Invincible Records) is available to buy from iTunes, Amazon &amp; HMV.\n\nTERMINAL GODS // www.terminal-gods.co.uk\n\nFormed in the Summer of 2011, Terminal Gods quickly established themselves as strong contenders on the London rock circuit.\n\nTheir captivating live shows highlight how rock music should be played and call upon influences that range from Judas Priest to Sisters of Mercy and Killing Joke to The Danse Society and sit in between modern bands such Interpol, Hurts, Ulterior and O Children.\n\nYou can buy their debut single ‘Electric Eyes’ from www.terminal-gods.co.uk\n\n“The icy guitars and machine-made beats lend an industrial feel to these new-wave styled tracks, with \'Electric Eyes\' providing a menacing and confident burst of Cult-ish pomp and power” Sounds XP\n\nSCARLET ECHO // www.facebook.com/scarletecho\n\nCharging adrenaline fueled female fronted rock from Bilericay, Scarlet Echo call upon influences that range from The Clash to Black Rebel Motorcycle Club.\n\nThey take these influences and make a sound their own of stadium sized hooks that can’t fail to draw you in. The powerful vocals of Hannah Stanbury and spiky guitar of Paul Braham propel them into in your face rock and roll.\n\nThey wont fail to entertain you.\n\nTHE BRASSIC // www.thebrassic.com\n\nChanneling the spirit of Quadrophenia this Falconwood quintet The Brassic ooze the swagger of The Who, The Jam, The Faces and Ian Dury and the Blockheads with pop infused rock and ska sensibilities that slaps you around the face with a cheeky grin,\n\nThey have already supported The Ordinary Boys and have a raucous live reputations, The Brassic will be bringing the party to The Dashwood.\n\n“They are arrogant and brash; backing it up with short sharp tunes that scream Radio play” Louder Than War\n\nTHE GAA GAA\'S // www.thegaagaas.co.uk\n\nThe Gaa Gaa’s combine The Cure like twisted hooks and nods towards Killing Joke and Siouxsie &amp; The Banshees.\n\nThey will be playing Jersey Live festival on 1st September alongside Noel Gallagher, Maverick Sabre, Primal Scream, The Stranglers and Professor Green.\n\nDebut single ‘Voltaire’ was produced by James Aparicio (Nick Cave/Mogwai) and mastered by Robert Harder (Brian Eno/The Slits) and was released on Playground Records. New single ‘Statues’ to follow.\n\n\"I love it when bands look like bands and I\'m always reminded of that when I see various members of The Gaa Gaas walking around Brighton in their raven like thatch.\" Simon Price (The Independent)\n\n\"I expect great things from these fuzzed-up freaks.\" God Is In The TV\n\nCERI JAMES // www.cerijames.com\n\nA favourite from the first Dashwoodstock last year, Ceri James returns with his enigmatic blend of Beatles inspired pop. His first solo album Start &amp; Begin was released in June 2008 but prior to this date he released a track on the first Angular CD as The Bridge which was voted No 1 compilation 2004 by NME.\n\nHe has supported Art Brut, Glenn Tilbrook, Mark Morriss (Bluetones), and Tom Hingley (Inspirals). His second solo album was released in Sep 2009 entitled Win, Lose and Some You Can\'t Tell. He is currently working on his 3rd studio album.\n\n\"While the 60\'s, 70\'s and 80\'s influences are loud and clear, the overall sound is nevertheless very much James\'s own and is something to savour.....\" R2 Magazine\n\nFIELD OF WOLVES // www.fieldofwolves.com\n\nThe hypnotic and achingly melancholic vocals of Field of Wolves, aka Holly Bestic, tiptoes on the gentle hum of an acoustic guitar as her voice barely reaches above a whisper before it submerges itself into a moment of soft and chilling trip-hop creating an awareness of isolation and haunting reflection.\n\nBorn and raised in Sydney, she relocated to London in 2008. She has developed her Dinah Washington and Billie Holliday inspired songs into something altogether more refreshing; which sits her into a bold territory recalling moments of modern jazz inspired female vocalists such as Martina Topley-Bird. All of this is immersed in the gentle crackle of Morcheeba and Massive Attack territory.\n\n“There’s so many neat diverse textures and layers to sample here. It’s trip-hop, it’s chill, and it jams” Blah Blah Blah Science\n\n\nRICHIR PHILLIPS //  www.richiephillips.net\n\nSinger-songwriter Richie Phillips already has two singles to his name and he occupies a space where his brittle and cracked vocals yearn over his gently strummed guitar.\n\nIts heartbreak blues but its modern take that recalls artists such as Elliott Smith, Ryan Adams and Richard Hawley.\n\nRichie is a special talent and it’s a pleasure to have him at Dashwoodstock 2012.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n', 'Thamesmead\'s \'Dashwoodstock 2012\'', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'thamesmeads-dashwoodstock-2012', '', '', '2012-08-18 21:02:48', '2012-08-18 19:02:48', '', '0', 'http://localhost/wordpress_old_css/?p=820', '0', 'ai1ec_event', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('821', '0', '2012-08-18 21:02:47', '2012-08-18 19:02:47', 'Giunge alla quarta edizione Vogue Fashion’s Night Out, la manifestazione dedicata allo shopping e alla moda organizzata da Vogue Italia, che negli anni passati ha riscosso un crescente successo internazionale. Un evento unico per vivere da vicino il mondo fashion in una veste festosa e densa di iniziative. La data di Milano del 6 Settembre 2012, tappa inaugurale che precede Roma e Firenze, avrà come scenario principale il quadrilatero della moda.\n\nIn questa occasione, la boutique Dirk Bikkembergs Manzoni 47 si trasformerà nel palcoscenico di Diskopolitan, il party eclettico e glamour del giovedì firmato Blanco Milano – locale di riferimento, dall’aperitivo in poi, per tutto il pubblico creativo e fashion milanese.\n\nDalla collaborazione con lo store Serendeepity e il progetto Discosafari nasce il concept musicale della serata: in console saranno ospiti i The Barking Dogs, duo italiano di Djs e producers tra i nuovi protagonisti della scena elettronica internazionale. Insieme a loro troveremo ai dischi lo storico dj torinese Lorenzo LSP e l’ideatore di Diskopolitan, Chris Jezus.\n\nTra musica e special drinks, il pubblico sarà il vero protagonista: lo spazio esterno della boutique diventerà infatti una passerella ancora più colorata, grazie agli interventi di live painting in sgargianti toni fluo.\n\nDunque porte aperte per un evento imperdibile presso il Flagship Store Dirk Bikkembergs Manzoni 47, giovedì 6 Settembre dalle ore 19:00 alle 22.30.\n\n* dopo le 22.30 il party proseguirà al Blanco Milano, Via Giovanni Battista Morgagni, 2 (a pochi minuti di distanza).\n\nhttp://www.bikkembergs.com/\nhttp://discosafari.com/the-barking-dogs/\nhttp://blancomilano.com/\nhttp://serendeepity.net/\n', 'DIRK BIKKEMBERGS per VFNO 2012 Milano', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'dirk-bikkembergs-per-vfno-2012-milano', '', '', '2012-08-18 21:02:49', '2012-08-18 19:02:49', '', '0', 'http://localhost/wordpress_old_css/?p=821', '0', 'ai1ec_event', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('822', '0', '2012-08-18 21:02:47', '2012-08-18 19:02:47', 'Uber presents\nLOCAL TALK PARTY\nw/ MAD MATS\n\nSaturday 01 September\nBull’s Head, Moseley\n\nWe celebrate 2 years at Bull’s Head with a special Local Talk Records party. \n\n-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nDJs\nMAD MATS [Local Talk]\nPETER OAKDEN [True Rebels]\nPAUL GRIFF\nGARY WARD\nRICHIE BARTHEZ\n\n-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nIt’s been two years since we (Paul Griff &amp; Gary Ward) combined the Days Like This and Uber parties to form Together... In that time we’ve had some amazing guests, some memorable parties, a name change and played some of the best music you’ll ever hear. We’re having so much fun putting these parties on, and there’s plenty more to come.\n\nTo celebrate this occassion we’ve invited Mad Mats from Stockholm and his Local Talk record label to party with us. Local Talk is such a quality label, transending genres with its music, and we’ve loved every release. One of the two men behind this great label just so happens to be one of our favourite DJs.... Mad Mats! We know many of you missed the packed out party with Mats last year where he took the roof off the Bulls Head, so here’s your opportunity to see why he produced one of the best sets of the year for us.\n\nJoining Mad Mats are the Uber regulars, Paul Griff, Gary Ward, Richie Barthez and the now jockanese Peter Oakden from the True Rebels, who have a release out on Local Talk very soon. We’ve missed the lad and are looking forward to him making the journey down from Scotland on the 1st.\n\nSee you there.\n\n10pm – 2am\nUpstairs at The Bulls Head\nSt. Mary’s Row, Moseley, Birmingham, B13 8HW\n\n£4 / £5 entry\nwww.thelocaltalk.de\nwww.facebook.com/uberparty\n', 'UBER pres. LOCAL TALK | MAD MATS | SAT 01 SEPT @ BULL\'S HEAD', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'uber-pres-local-talk-mad-mats-sat-01-sept-bulls-head', '', '', '2012-08-18 21:02:47', '2012-08-18 19:02:47', '', '0', 'http://localhost/wordpress_old_css/?p=822', '0', 'ai1ec_event', '', '0');
